Constant MIR_DEBUG_SCOPE as Integer is 20803          Note: Lexical scope marker

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MIR Core Type Definitions
Note: Using TIER 3 (OWNED HEAP) allocation - permanent structures across passes
Note: All sizes calculated based on 64-bit pointers (8 bytes each)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The MIR uses a base node type that can represent any instruction in SSA form.
Unlike HIR which tracks full AST structure, MIR is a flat list of instructions
organized into basic blocks with explicit control flow edges.

Each instruction produces at most one SSA value (single assignment property).
Instructions with multiple results (like divmod) are split into multiple
instructions. This simplifies data flow analysis and optimization.
@End Reasoning

Type called "MIRNode":
    opcode as Integer              Note: MIR opcode constant (20000-20999)
    value_id as Integer            Note: SSA ID this instruction defines (0 if none)
    operand1 as Integer            Note: First operand value ID (0 if unused)
    operand2 as Integer            Note: Second operand value ID (0 if unused)
    operand3 as Integer            Note: Third operand value ID (0 if unused)
    type_info as Integer           Note: Pointer to HIRTypeInfo for result type
    next as Integer                Note: Pointer to next instruction in block (0 if last)
    parent_block as Integer        Note: Pointer to containing MIRBasicBlock
    metadata as Integer            Note: Optional metadata pointer (0 if none)
End Type

Note: Size: 9 fields * 8 bytes = 72 bytes per MIRNode

@Reasoning
MIRValue represents an SSA (virtual register). In SSA form, each
value is assigned exactly once. We track the defining instruction and all
uses to enable efficient def-use chain traversal for optimizations.

The use list enables rapid identification of all instructions that consume
this value, critical for dead code elimination, constant propagation, and
value numbering optimizations.
@End Reasoning

Type called "MIRValue":
    value_id as Integer            Note: Unique SSA ID (%0, %1, %2, ...)
    type_info as Integer           Note: Pointer to HIRTypeInfo
    def_instruction as Integer     Note: Pointer to instruction defining this value
    use_list as Integer            Note: Pointer to List of instructions using this value
    use_count as Integer           Note: Number of uses (cached for performance)
    is_constant as Integer         Note: Boolean: 1 if constant, 0 otherwise
    constant_value as Integer      Note: If constant, the actual value
End Type

Note: Size: 7 fields * 8 bytes = 56 bytes per MIRValue

@Reasoning
A basic block is a maximal sequence of instructions with:
- Single entry point (first instruction)
- Single exit point (terminator instruction)
- No internal control flow

Basic blocks are connected via predecessor/successor edges to form the
control flow graph (CFG). This structure enables efficient control flow
analysis and optimization passes.

Phi nodes are special instructions placed at the beginning of blocks that
have multiple predecessors, implementing SSA value merging.
@End Reasoning

Type called "MIRBasicBlock":
    block_id as Integer            Note: Unique block identifier
    label as Integer               Note: Pointer to block label string
    instructions as Integer        Note: Pointer to List of MIRNode instructions
    instruction_count as Integer   Note: Number of instructions in block
    predecessors as Integer        Note: Pointer to List of predecessor block IDs
    predecessor_count as Integer   Note: Number of predecessors
    successors as Integer          Note: Pointer to List of successor block IDs
    successor_count as Integer     Note: Number of successors
    dominator as Integer           Note: Immediate dominator block ID (-1 if entry)
    loop_depth as Integer          Note: Nesting depth in loops (0 if not in loop)
    is_loop_header as Integer      Note: Boolean: 1 if loop header, 0 otherwise
    phi_nodes as Integer           Note: Pointer to List of phi node instructions
End Type

Note: Size: 12 fields * 8 bytes = 96 bytes per MIRBasicBlock

@Reasoning
The control flow graph (CFG) represents the flow of control between basic blocks.
It maintains entry and exit blocks, all blocks in the function, and explicit edges.

Dominance information is computed lazily and cached for efficiency. SSA form
validity is tracked to ensure optimization passes maintain SSA properties.
@End Reasoning

Type called "MIRCFG":
    entry_block as Integer         Note: Pointer to entry basic block
    exit_block as Integer          Note: Pointer to exit basic block (may be synthetic)
    blocks as Integer              Note: Pointer to List of all basic blocks
    block_count as Integer         Note: Number of blocks
    edges as Integer               Note: Pointer to List of CFG edge tuples (pred, succ)
    edge_count as Integer          Note: Number of edges
    next_block_id as Integer       Note: Counter for generating unique block IDs
    dominance_computed as Integer  Note: Boolean: 1 if dominance info valid, 0 otherwise
    ssa_form as Integer            Note: Boolean: 1 if in valid SSA form, 0 otherwise
End Type

Note: Size: 9 fields * 8 bytes = 72 bytes per MIRCFG

@Reasoning
A MIR function encapsulates the SSA form of a single function. It owns the CFG,
all SSA values, parameters, and metadata. The next_value_id counter ensures
unique SSA IDs are generated throughout the function.

External functions (imported from other modules or C libraries) have no CFG
and are marked with is_external flag.
@End Reasoning

Type called "MIRFunction":
    name as Integer                Note: Offset 0  - Pointer to function name string
    cfg as Integer                 Note: Offset 8  - Pointer to MIRCFG
    parameters as Integer          Note: Offset 16 - Pointer to List of parameter value IDs
    parameter_count as Integer     Note: Offset 24 - Number of parameters
    return_type as Integer         Note: Offset 32 - Pointer to HIRTypeInfo for return type
    local_values as Integer        Note: Offset 40 - Pointer to List of all SSA values in function
    value_count as Integer         Note: Offset 48 - Number of SSA values
    next_value_id as Integer       Note: Offset 56 - Counter for generating unique value IDs
    value_to_instruction as Integer Note: Offset 64 - Dictionary mapping value_id -> defining instruction pointer
    hir_node as Integer            Note: Offset 72 - Pointer to original HIR process definition
    is_external as Integer         Note: Offset 80 - Boolean: 1 if external function, 0 if defined (authoritative offset)
    metadata as Integer            Note: Offset 88 - Optional metadata pointer
    library_name as Integer        Note: Offset 96 - P2-D FFI: Pointer to library name string (0 if not external)
    alias_name as Integer          Note: Offset 104 - P2-D FFI: Pointer to C-side symbol name (0 if same as name)
    convention_id as Integer       Note: Offset 112 - P2-D FFI: Calling convention ID (0=c, 1=stdcall, 2=fastcall, 3=cdecl, 4=syscall, 5=objc)
End Type

Note: Size: 15 fields * 8 bytes = 120 bytes per MIRFunction
Note: P2-D extension: library_name (offset 96), alias_name (offset 104), convention_id (offset 112)
Note: Authoritative is_external offset is 80 (matches all consumers: inlining, devirt, tail_call, lto, lir_builder).

@Reasoning
The top-level MIR program container owns all functions, global values, and
string constants. It references the HIR type table to avoid duplicating type
information across IR layers.

This structure serves as the root for the entire MIR representation and is
passed through the optimization pipeline.
@End Reasoning

Type called "MIRProgram":
    functions as Integer           Note: Pointer to List of MIRFunction pointers
    function_count as Integer      Note: Number of functions
    global_values as Integer       Note: Pointer to List of global SSA values
    global_count as Integer        Note: Number of globals
    string_constants as Integer    Note: Pointer to List of string literal pointers
    string_count as Integer        Note: Number of string constants
    type_table as Integer          Note: Reference to HIR type table (shared)
    metadata as Integer            Note: Program-level metadata pointer
End Type

Note: Size: 8 fields * 8 bytes = 64 bytes per MIRProgram

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MIR Core Creation Functions
Note: All allocations use TIER 3 (OWNED HEAP) - permanent structures
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Allocates and initialises a fresh MIRNode — the unit of three-address SSA in
this IR. Every instruction the compiler will ever optimise, schedule, or lower
flows through this constructor, so the layout and initial-state guarantees
established here are load-bearing for every downstream pass (verifier, DCE,
inliner, LIR builder, register allocator).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates 72 bytes on the owned heap (TIER 3) — matching the 9-field MIRNode
type — and zero-initialises all fields except opcode (offset 0). value_id
(offset 8) starts at 0 to mark the instruction as non-producing until the
caller assigns one, and operand1/2/3 (offsets 16/24/32), type_info (40),
next (48), parent_block (56), and metadata (64) all start at 0. Returns 0
if allocation fails, allowing the caller to abort safely.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Heap allocation followed by deterministic field writes through fixed offsets
within the 72-byte block; no unchecked pointer arithmetic. Failure to allocate
returns 0 rather than dereferencing a null pointer.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_mir_node" that takes opcode as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node_size be 72
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, opcode
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, 0

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning
Allocates and initialises a fresh MIRValue — the SSA virtual-register record
that anchors def-use tracking. Every optimisation pass that walks def-use
chains (constant propagation, value numbering, DCE, copy propagation,
mem2reg) reads from the structure created here, so the freshly-zeroed
use-list and use-count established at construction are a precondition for
those passes' correctness.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates 56 bytes (7 fields, TIER 3 owned heap) and writes value_id at
offset 0 and type_info at offset 8. def_instruction (offset 16) is zeroed —
the caller must call set_value_def once the producing instruction exists.
use_list (offset 24) gets a fresh List, use_count (offset 32) starts at 0,
and is_constant (40) / constant_value (48) start at 0. Returns 0 on
allocation failure.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Heap allocation followed by field initialisation through fixed offsets in a
56-byte block. The use_list backing store is independently allocated by
List.create; any failure of that sub-allocation propagates a null pointer
that subsequent add_value_use / remove_value_use calls must tolerate.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_mir_value" that takes value_id as Integer, type_info as Integer returns Integer:
    Let value_size be 56
    Let value be proc allocate from Layout with value_size

    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with value, 0, value_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with value, 8, type_info
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with value, 16, 0

    Let use_list be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with value, 24, use_list
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with value, 32, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with value, 40, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with value, 48, 0

    Return value
End Process

@Reasoning
Allocates and initialises a fresh MIRBasicBlock — the node type of the CFG.
Every control-flow analysis (dominance, loop detection, liveness, scheduling)
and every transformation that splits or merges control flow operates on these
records, so the empty-instruction / empty-edge / unset-dominator initial
state established here is the contract every CFG-mutating pass relies on.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates 96 bytes (12 fields, TIER 3 owned heap). Writes block_id at offset
0 and label pointer at offset 8. Creates fresh Lists for instructions (16),
predecessors (32), successors (48), phi_nodes (88), and zeroes their
respective counts (24, 40, 56). Sets dominator (offset 64) to -1 to encode
"not yet computed", and zeroes loop_depth (72) and is_loop_header (80).
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Heap allocation followed by deterministic field writes through fixed offsets
in a 96-byte block. Four sub-allocations for the embedded Lists; any null
from List.create yields a block whose iteration loops will simply be no-ops
(length 0), so partial allocation does not produce dangling reads.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_mir_basic_block" that takes block_id as Integer, label as Integer returns Integer:
    Let block_size be 96
    Let block be proc allocate from Layout with block_size

    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 0, block_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 8, label

    Let instructions be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 16, instructions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 24, 0

    Let predecessors be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 32, predecessors
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 40, 0

    Let successors be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 48, successors
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 56, 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 64, -1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 72, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 80, 0

    Let phi_nodes be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 88, phi_nodes

    Return block
End Process

@Reasoning
Allocates the per-function MIRCFG that owns the block list, edge list, and
the per-function block-id counter. The CFG is the substrate on which every
control-flow pass runs (dominance, loops, mem2reg, scheduling, lowering),
and several of those passes assume entry and exit are settable but not
required at construction, and that ssa_form / dominance_computed start at
"invalid" so passes know to (re)compute them.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates 72 bytes (9 fields, TIER 3 owned heap). Zeroes entry_block (0)
and exit_block (8) — set later by set_cfg_entry_block / set_cfg_exit_block.
Creates fresh Lists for blocks (offset 16) and edges (offset 32) and zeroes
their counts (24, 40). next_block_id (48), dominance_computed (56), and
ssa_form (64) all start at 0. Returns 0 if allocation fails.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Heap allocation plus two sub-allocations for the embedded Lists. All field
writes go through fixed offsets within the 72-byte record; null returns
from List.create propagate as empty backing stores rather than dangling
pointers.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_mir_cfg" returns Integer:
    Let cfg_size be 72
    Let cfg be proc allocate from Layout with cfg_size

    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 8, 0

    Let blocks be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16, blocks
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24, 0

    Let edges be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 32, edges
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 40, 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 48, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 56, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 64, 0

    Return cfg
End Process

@Reasoning
Allocates and initialises the MIRFunction record — the unit of compilation
inside the MIR program. Every later pass (inlining, devirtualisation, tail
call, LTO, LIR lowering) reads through this record's authoritative offsets
(name, cfg, parameters, return_type, value_to_instruction map, is_external,
FFI fields), so the offsets and zero-initialised invariants set here are a
hard contract shared with every consumer. The retained hir_node reference
also lets diagnostics map MIR-level errors back to source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates 120 bytes (15 fields, TIER 3 owned heap). Writes name at offset 0,
creates a fresh MIRCFG at offset 8, creates parameter List at offset 16 with
count 0 at offset 24, writes return_type at 32, creates the local-values
List at 40 with count 0 at 48 and next_value_id seeded 0 at 56, allocates
the value_to_instruction Dictionary at offset 64, writes hir_node at 72,
zeroes is_external at the authoritative offset 80, zeroes metadata at 88,
and zeroes the three P2-D FFI fields library_name (96), alias_name (104),
convention_id (112). Returns 0 if allocation fails.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Heap allocation plus three sub-allocations (CFG, two Lists, Dictionary). The
is_external flag MUST be written at offset 80 specifically — every consumer
(inlining, devirt, tail_call, lto, lir_builder) reads at offset 80, and a
mismatch here would silently corrupt FFI dispatch.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_mir_function" that takes name as Integer, return_type as Integer, hir_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let function_size be 120
    Let function be proc allocate from Layout with function_size

    If function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: name (offset 0)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 0, name

    Note: cfg (offset 8)
    Let cfg be proc create_mir_cfg
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 8, cfg

    Note: parameters list (offset 16), parameter_count (offset 24)
    Let parameters be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 16, parameters
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 24, 0

    Note: return_type (offset 32)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 32, return_type

    Note: local_values list (offset 40), value_count (offset 48), next_value_id (offset 56)
    Let local_values be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 40, local_values
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 48, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 56, 0

    Note: value_to_instruction dictionary (offset 64) - CRITICAL for metadata lookup
    Let value_map be proc create from Dictionary
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 64, value_map

    Note: hir_node (offset 72), is_external (offset 80), metadata (offset 88)
    Note: Authoritative offset for is_external is 80 — all consumers (inlining, devirt,
    Note: tail_call, lto, lir_builder) read at offset 80. The Type definition above
    Note: declares is_external at offset 80 to match. New functions are non-external (=0).
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 72, hir_node
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 80, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 88, 0

    Note: P2-D FFI extension fields:
    Note:   library_name (offset 96), alias_name (offset 104), convention_id (offset 112)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 96, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 104, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 112, 0

    Return function
End Process

@Reasoning
Marks a MIRFunction as external (FFI binding) and records the metadata that
the LIR builder, inliner, devirtualizer, tail-call pass, and LTO link layer
need in order to emit a proper extern symbol reference rather than an
in-module definition. Without this metadata, an externally-imported function
would be lowered as an empty body and the linker would emit unresolved-symbol
errors at static-link time.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Sets is_external = 1 at offset 80 (the authoritative offset matching the Type
definition and every consumer pass) and stores the three FFI fields:
library_name (96), alias_name (104), and convention_id (112). The convention_id
follows the wire encoding established by the FFI primitives: 0 = CDecl,
1 = StdCall, 2 = FastCall, 3 = SysV. Null function pointer returns 0 to allow
the caller to fail safely without mutating arbitrary memory.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Direct memory writes via memory_set_int64 occur only after a null check on the
function pointer. No bounds checking is required because the offsets are fixed
constants inside the 120-byte MIRFunction layout established by
create_mir_function.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "mir_function_set_external" that takes function as Integer, library_name as Integer, alias_name as Integer, convention_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: P2-D FFI: Mark a MIRFunction as external and record FFI metadata.
    Note: Sets is_external=1 (at offset 80 per consumer-side convention) plus FFI fields.
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set is_external = 1 at offset 80 (authoritative — matches Type definition
    Note: and all consumers: inlining, devirt, tail_call, lto, lir_builder).
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 80, 1

    Note: Set FFI metadata fields (offsets 96/104/112)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 96, library_name
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 104, alias_name
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 112, convention_id

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Reads the P2-D FFI library_name pointer that the LIR builder and the linker
front-end use to emit the correct extern symbol reference for an
externally-imported function. A null library_name means "no explicit
library" — the linker then resolves the symbol against the default
namespace. Every consumer that emits extern references (lir_builder, lto,
the bytecode emitter) calls this accessor to obtain the FFI binding.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 stored at MIRFunction offset 96 (the authoritative library_name
slot established by create_mir_function and mir_function_set_external).
Returns 0 for a null function pointer to allow safe handling of partial
records.
@End Implementation

Process called "mir_function_get_library_name" that takes function as Integer returns Integer:
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function, 96
End Process

@Reasoning
Reads the P2-D FFI alias_name pointer — the C-side symbol name that the
emitter must use when this name differs from the Runa-side function name
(e.g. when binding to a C library function whose name conflicts with a Runa
keyword or naming convention). If alias_name is 0, the function name itself
(offset 0) is returned, encoding the rule "no alias means the Runa name IS
the C symbol".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRFunction offset 104. When the read returns 0, falls
back to reading the function name at offset 0, implementing the "alias
defaults to name" rule that the lir_builder and FFI emitter rely on. Returns
0 for a null function pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "mir_function_get_alias_name" that takes function as Integer returns Integer:
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let alias be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function, 104
    If alias is equal to 0:
        Note: Default alias is the function name (offset 0)
        Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function, 0
    End If
    Return alias
End Process

@Reasoning
Reads the P2-D FFI calling-convention id. The id selects the ABI the LIR
builder and machine-code emitter use to lower call sites: 0 = CDecl,
1 = StdCall, 2 = FastCall, 3 = SysV, 4 = SystemCall, 5 = ObjC. The wrong
convention would produce miscompiled call sequences (wrong register usage,
wrong stack cleanup), so this accessor's correctness is critical for FFI
correctness on every architecture.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 stored at MIRFunction offset 112. Returns 0 (CDecl, the
safe default) for a null function pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "mir_function_get_convention_id" that takes function as Integer returns Integer:
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function, 112
End Process

@Reasoning
Allocates and initialises the MIRProgram — the root container for the
entire MIR representation that flows through the optimisation pipeline.
Optimisation drivers, the LTO link layer, and the LIR builder all start
from this record, so its empty-but-valid initial state (empty function
list, empty globals, empty string constants, shared HIR type table) is
the precondition every pass driver relies on.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates 64 bytes (8 fields, TIER 3 owned heap). Creates fresh Lists for
functions (offset 0), global_values (16), and string_constants (32), with
their counts (8, 24, 40) zeroed. Writes the shared type_table at offset 48
(by reference — never duplicated, the HIR is the single owner). metadata
at offset 56 starts at 0. Returns 0 if allocation fails.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Heap allocation plus three List sub-allocations. The type_table pointer is
borrowed, not owned — destroying the MIRProgram MUST NOT free the type
table, which has HIR-level lifetime that outlives MIR.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_mir_program" that takes type_table as Integer returns Integer:
    Let program_size be 64
    Let program be proc allocate from Layout with program_size

    If program is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let functions be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 0, functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 8, 0

    Let global_values be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 16, global_values
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 24, 0

    Let string_constants be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 32, string_constants
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 40, 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 48, type_table
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 56, 0

    Return program
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MIR Access and Modification Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns an instruction's opcode — the single field that determines instruction
shape for every consumer (the verifier checks operand arity by opcode, the
optimiser dispatches transformations by opcode, the LIR lowering pass selects
machine instructions by opcode). Because opcode classification is needed in
almost every pass, this read is on the inner hot loop of essentially every
MIR walk.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRNode offset 0 (the canonical opcode slot established
by create_mir_node). Returns 0 for a null node pointer; 0 is MIR_NOP, which
is the safe interpretation of "no instruction".
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Inner-loop accessor. Always inlines to a single load on x86_64; the null
check predicts cleanly. Called by every pass that walks instructions.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "get_mir_node_opcode" that takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Mutates an instruction's opcode. Used by peephole optimisation and strength
reduction to rewrite an instruction in place rather than allocating a new
MIRNode — preserving the existing value_id, operand slots, and def-use
linkage. In-place opcode rewriting avoids touching the use-list which would
require a use-list rewrite for every consumer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes opcode at MIRNode offset 0. Returns 1 on success, 0 for a null node
pointer. Does not validate that the new opcode is compatible with the
existing operand layout — that is the caller's responsibility (peephole
rules enforce shape compatibility before invoking this mutator).
@End Implementation

Process called "set_mir_node_opcode" that takes node as Integer, opcode as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, opcode
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the SSA value-id that this instruction defines (the "destination
register" in three-address code). A 0 here means the instruction is
non-producing (store, branch, return, nop). The verifier and DCE both read
this field to classify producers vs side-effect-only instructions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRNode offset 8. Returns 0 for null node; 0 is
indistinguishable from "non-producing" but the caller can call
produces_value(opcode) for that distinction when needed.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Inner-loop accessor; read on every def-use walk. Inlines to a single load.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "get_mir_node_value_id" that takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Assigns or rewrites the SSA value-id of an instruction. Used by SSA
construction (to attach a freshly allocated value-id to a defining
instruction) and by value-renaming passes that retag a definition during
copy propagation. The companion register_value_definition / replace_all_uses
must keep the value-to-instruction map and def-use chain in sync after
this write.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes value_id at MIRNode offset 8. Returns 1 on success, 0 for null node.
Does not update the value_to_instruction map — the caller must call
register_value_definition separately to maintain map invariants.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_mir_node_value_id" that takes node as Integer, value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, value_id
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Reads one of an instruction's three operand slots (operand1, operand2,
operand3). MIR uses a fixed three-operand encoding because the vast majority
of three-address-code instructions need at most that many — calls with more
than two arguments use a separate side-channel argument list rather than
expanding this slot count, keeping MIRNode at a stable 64-byte layout.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Dispatches on operand_index (1-based to match the human-facing convention used
elsewhere in the SSA construction code) and returns the value-id stored at the
corresponding fixed offset: 16 for operand1, 24 for operand2, 32 for operand3.
Returns 0 for null node or any out-of-range operand_index, which the caller
must interpret as "no such operand" since 0 is not a valid SSA value-id.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_mir_node_operand" that takes node as Integer, operand_index as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If operand_index is equal to 1:
        Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
    End If

    If operand_index is equal to 2:
        Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24
    End If

    If operand_index is equal to 3:
        Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Writes a new value-id into one of the instruction's three operand slots.
This is the canonical mutator used by SSA renaming, copy/constant propagation,
and value numbering — passes that need to redirect a use without changing
the instruction's opcode or other operands.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Mirrors get_mir_node_operand: dispatches on the 1-based operand_index and
writes value_id at offset 16, 24, or 32. Returns 1 on successful write or 0
for null node / out-of-range index. The caller is responsible for updating
def-use chains (add_value_use / remove_value_use) — this function only
mutates the slot.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_mir_node_operand" that takes node as Integer, operand_index as Integer, value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If operand_index is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, value_id
        Return 1
    End If

    If operand_index is equal to 2:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, value_id
        Return 1
    End If

    If operand_index is equal to 3:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, value_id
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the HIRTypeInfo pointer for the value this instruction produces.
The type drives instruction selection (different machine instructions for
i32 vs i64 vs f64), register-class selection (GPR vs FPR vs vector), and
calling-convention placement (integer args vs SSE args). Every backend pass
that lowers MIR to machine code reads through this accessor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRNode offset 40 (the canonical type_info slot per the
Type definition). Returns 0 for null node, which downstream lowering MUST
treat as a type-erased instruction (an error in normal flow).
@End Implementation

Process called "get_mir_node_type" that takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 40
End Process

@Reasoning
Sets the HIRTypeInfo pointer for an instruction's result. Used by SSA
construction when wiring instructions to their declared result type, and by
type-rewriting passes (sign extension insertion, vector lowering) that
generate new instructions with derived types.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes type_info at MIRNode offset 40. Returns 1 on success, 0 for null
node. The type pointer is borrowed from the HIR type table; the caller
must NOT pass a heap-owned type that could be freed before this MIRNode.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_mir_node_type" that takes node as Integer, type_info as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, type_info
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the MIRBasicBlock pointer that contains this instruction. The parent
back-pointer enables passes that walk instructions independently of blocks
(e.g. iterating a global def-use list) to navigate back to control-flow
context — needed by loop analysis, dominance checks, and the verifier when
checking that uses dominate definitions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRNode offset 56 (the canonical parent_block slot).
Returns 0 for null node or for an instruction not yet linked into a block.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_mir_node_parent_block" that takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 56
End Process

@Reasoning
Sets an instruction's parent-block back-pointer. Used by
add_instruction_to_block and insert_instruction_at_block_start whenever the
instruction is linked into a block, and by code-motion passes (LICM, GVN
PRE) that relocate instructions across blocks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes block pointer at MIRNode offset 56. Returns 1 on success, 0 for
null node. The block pointer is a borrowed reference — the block owns the
instruction, not vice versa.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_mir_node_parent_block" that takes node as Integer, block as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, block
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the HIRTypeInfo pointer associated with an SSA value. Type analysis,
register-class assignment, and constant-folding rules all dispatch on the
value's type — for instance, addition of two i32 values lowers to a 32-bit
ADD whereas i64 addition lowers to a 64-bit ADD on x86_64.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRValue offset 8 (the type_info slot per the Type
definition). Returns 0 for null value pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_value_type" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with value, 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the instruction that defines this SSA value — the "def" side of
the def-use chain. SSA's single-assignment invariant guarantees this is
well-defined: exactly one instruction in the function writes any given
value. Used by GVN, copy propagation, and the verifier (to check that
defs dominate all uses).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRValue offset 16 (the def_instruction slot). Returns
0 for null value pointer; a non-null value with def_instruction == 0
indicates an SSA value not yet linked to its producing instruction, which
is a transient state during SSA construction.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_value_def" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with value, 16
End Process

@Reasoning
Sets the defining instruction for an SSA value. Called during SSA
construction once both the MIRValue record and the producing MIRNode exist
and need to be linked. SSA's single-assignment property means this should
be called exactly once per value over its lifetime; subsequent rewrites
constitute an SSA-invariant violation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes instruction pointer at MIRValue offset 16. Returns 1 on success, 0
for null value. Does not enforce single-assignment — that contract is the
caller's responsibility (SSA construction passes call this once at value
creation; transforms preserve it by allocating new values instead of
re-defining existing ones).
@End Implementation

Process called "set_value_def" that takes value as Integer, instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with value, 16, instruction
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the cached use-count of an SSA value — the number of instructions
currently consuming this value. DCE uses this directly (zero uses + no side
effect ⇒ dead) and GVN uses it to decide whether a redundant computation is
worth eliminating (one use ⇒ cheap to inline, many uses ⇒ keep).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRValue offset 32 (the use_count slot, maintained by
add_value_use and remove_value_use). Returns 0 for null value pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Inner-loop accessor — DCE reads this on every instruction. Inlines to a
single load.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "get_value_use_count" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with value, 32
End Process

@Reasoning
Records that an instruction uses this SSA value. The def-use chain is the
core data structure backing every optimisation that needs to find consumers
of a definition: DCE (find values with zero uses), constant propagation
(rewrite all consumers when a value becomes constant), copy propagation,
value numbering, mem2reg promotion, and replace_all_uses.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Appends the instruction to the use_list at MIRValue offset 24 and increments
the cached use_count at offset 32. Returns 1 on success or 0 if either
pointer is null. The use_count is cached (rather than recomputed from
list length) because get_value_use_count is on the inner loop of DCE.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Mutates a List backing store and a counter. Null checks gate both writes;
no unchecked allocation occurs (the use_list was allocated at value
creation).
@End Security_Scope

@Performance_Hints
Called for every operand of every instruction created by SSA construction
and by every optimiser that introduces new uses. The List append is
amortised O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "add_value_use" that takes value as Integer, instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let use_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with value, 24
    proc append from List with use_list, instruction

    Let use_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with value, 32
    Set use_count to use_count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with value, 32, use_count

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Removes an instruction from a value's use list — the inverse of
add_value_use. Called whenever an instruction is deleted (DCE), retargeted
to a different operand (constant propagation, copy propagation,
replace_all_uses), or rewritten so it no longer reads this value. Stale
use-list entries would corrupt every subsequent DCE / GVN decision, so this
must run on every operand mutation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Scans the use_list at MIRValue offset 24 linearly for the instruction. On
match, shifts subsequent entries left by one (compacting the list) and
decrements use_count at offset 32. Returns 1 on found-and-removed, 0 if
the instruction was not in the use list. Linear scan is acceptable because
typical use counts are small; if a value has hundreds of uses the optimiser
should already have eliminated most of them.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Mutates the use_list backing store and the cached use_count. Null checks on
both pointers; list-index arithmetic bounded by the cached list length.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "remove_value_use" that takes value as Integer, instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let use_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with value, 24
    Let list_len be proc length from List with use_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than list_len:
        Let use_inst be proc get from List with use_list, i
        If use_inst is equal to instruction:
            Note: Found the use, remove it by shifting remaining elements
            Let j be i
            While j is less than list_len minus 1:
                Let next_use be proc get from List with use_list, j plus 1
                proc set from List with use_list, j, next_use
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While

            Let use_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with value, 32
            Set use_count to use_count minus 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with value, 32, use_count

            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: VALUE → INSTRUCTION MAPPING FUNCTIONS
Note: Critical infrastructure for metadata and variable name lookup
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Registers a value-id → defining-instruction binding in the function's
value_to_instruction dictionary. This second mapping (parallel to the
def_instruction field on MIRValue itself) exists so that passes which only
hold a value-id (e.g. operand walks that recover the producer for metadata
lookup) can recover the producing instruction in O(1) without scanning all
blocks. MUST be called whenever an instruction is created that produces a
value; failure to register breaks variable-name resolution in error
messages and breaks metadata propagation through optimisations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the value_to_instruction Dictionary at MIRFunction offset 64,
serialises value_id to a string key, and stores the inst_ptr under that
key. Returns 1 on success, 0 if any of function_ptr, inst_ptr, or
value_id is 0, or if the value map itself is null (uninitialised function).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Dictionary write; the integer-to-string conversion allocates a temporary
key string that the Dictionary copies internally. Null checks gate all
dereferences.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "register_value_definition" that takes function_ptr as Integer, value_id as Integer, inst_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If function_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If value_id is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get value_to_instruction map (offset 64 in MIRFunction)
    Let value_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function_ptr, 64

    If value_map is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Convert value_id to string for dictionary key
    Let value_id_str be proc integer_to_string from StringCore with value_id

    Note: Register mapping: value_id -> instruction
    proc set from Dictionary with value_map, value_id_str, inst_ptr

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Recovers the producing MIRNode for a given SSA value-id by querying the
function's value_to_instruction dictionary. This is the read companion to
register_value_definition; used by get_operand_variable_name (to look up a
source-level variable name for an operand) and by diagnostic / error
reporting code that needs to map an SSA id back to a concrete instruction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the value_to_instruction Dictionary at MIRFunction offset 64,
serialises value_id to a string key, and queries the dictionary. Returns
the stored instruction pointer or 0 if function_ptr is null, value_id is
0, the value map is uninitialised, or the value_id has no registered
producer (which can occur for constants and for values defined outside
this function).
@End Implementation

Process called "lookup_defining_instruction" that takes function_ptr as Integer, value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If function_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If value_id is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get value_to_instruction map (offset 64 in MIRFunction)
    Let value_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function_ptr, 64

    If value_map is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Convert value_id to string for dictionary key
    Let value_id_str be proc integer_to_string from StringCore with value_id

    Note: Lookup defining instruction
    Let inst_ptr be proc get from Dictionary with value_map, value_id_str

    Return inst_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning
Redirects every consumer of old_value to consume new_value instead. This
is the core primitive of constant propagation (rewrite every use of a
computed value with the constant), copy propagation (rewrite every use of
a copy with the original), and value numbering (rewrite every redundant
computation with the canonical representative). After this returns,
old_value is dead (zero uses) and DCE can remove its defining instruction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walks the use_list at MIRValue offset 24 of old_value. For each consuming
instruction, scans operand1 (offset 16), operand2 (24), and operand3 (32);
where the operand equals old_value, writes new_value in its place AND
calls add_value_use(new_value, inst) to register the new dependency.
After the scan, zeroes the cached use_count of old_value at offset 32.
Returns 1 on success, 0 if either pointer is null.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Reads through old_value's use list and writes to each instruction's operand
slots. Null checks gate both pointers. The use_list backing store is not
modified directly here — only the cached use_count is reset; subsequent
DCE deletes the value record and its use_list together.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "replace_all_uses" that takes old_value as Integer, new_value as Integer returns Integer:
    If old_value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If new_value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let use_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with old_value, 24
    Let use_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with old_value, 32
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than use_count:
        Let inst be proc get from List with use_list, i

        Let op1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16
        If op1 is equal to old_value:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst, 16, new_value
            proc add_value_use with new_value, inst
        End If

        Let op2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 24
        If op2 is equal to old_value:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst, 24, new_value
            proc add_value_use with new_value, inst
        End If

        Let op3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 32
        If op3 is equal to old_value:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst, 32, new_value
            proc add_value_use with new_value, inst
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Clear old value's use list and count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with old_value, 32, 0

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the instruction List of a basic block — the ordered sequence of
instructions that forms the block's body. Every traversal pass (DCE, GVN,
scheduling, register allocation, lowering) iterates this list. The list
is the canonical source of truth for block contents; instruction_count
is a cached length kept in sync by add_instruction_to_block /
insert_instruction_at_block_start.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRBasicBlock offset 16 (the instructions slot). Returns
0 for null block. The returned list is borrowed — callers must NOT free it;
its lifetime is tied to the block.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Inner-loop accessor; called on every block walk. Inlines to a single load.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "get_block_instructions" that takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the cached length of the block's instruction list. Used as the
loop bound by every block-walking pass; reading the cached count avoids
a function call into List.length on every iteration.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRBasicBlock offset 24 (the instruction_count slot,
kept in sync by add_instruction_to_block and
insert_instruction_at_block_start). Returns 0 for null block.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Read once before every block-instruction loop. Inlines to a single load.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "get_block_instruction_count" that takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24
End Process

@Reasoning
Appends an instruction to the end of a basic block's instruction list and
wires the instruction's parent_block back-pointer. Used by HIR-to-MIR
lowering when emitting instructions in source order, and by optimisation
passes that synthesise new instructions to append. Maintaining both the
forward link (block ⇒ inst list) and back-link (inst ⇒ parent block) in
the same operation prevents the inconsistency that arises if a pass forgets
to update one side.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the instructions List at MIRBasicBlock offset 16, appends instruction,
reads instruction_count at offset 24 and increments it, then writes
instruction's parent_block back-pointer at MIRNode offset 56. Returns 1 on
success, 0 if either pointer is null. Does NOT verify that the instruction
is not already in some other block — caller responsibility.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Three writes: List append, counter increment, back-pointer write. Null
checks gate every dereference; List append is itself bounds-safe (amortised
realloc).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "add_instruction_to_block" that takes block as Integer, instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
    proc append from List with instructions, instruction

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24
    Set count to count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block, 24, count

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with instruction, 56, block

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the List of predecessor block-ids — every block from which control
can enter this block. The predecessor list is the substrate of every
reverse CFG walk: dominance computation, phi-node placement (Cytron's
algorithm reads predecessors to determine merge points), and liveness
analysis (a live-in must propagate back to every predecessor's live-out).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRBasicBlock offset 32 (the predecessors slot, populated
by add_cfg_edge). Returns 0 for null block. List ownership belongs to the
block — callers must NOT free it.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_block_predecessors" that takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 32
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the cached predecessor count of a block. Used as the loop bound by
reverse CFG walks (dominance, liveness, phi placement) and as the test for
phi-node necessity: a block with predecessor_count >= 2 needs phis for any
value live across the merge.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRBasicBlock offset 40 (the predecessor_count slot,
maintained by add_cfg_edge). Returns 0 for null block.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Read once before every reverse CFG walk. Inlines to a single load.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "get_block_predecessor_count" that takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 40
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the List of successor block-ids — every block to which control
can flow from this block. The successor list drives every forward CFG
walk: reachability analysis, forward dataflow (available expressions,
reaching definitions), and emission ordering (a topological order over
successors yields a fall-through-friendly layout).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRBasicBlock offset 48 (the successors slot, populated
by add_cfg_edge). Returns 0 for null block; the list is borrowed.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_block_successors" that takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 48
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the cached successor count of a block. Used as the loop bound by
forward CFG walks; also used as the branch-shape classifier (count 0 ⇒
return / unwind, count 1 ⇒ unconditional jump or fall-through, count 2 ⇒
conditional branch, count > 2 ⇒ switch / indirect branch).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRBasicBlock offset 56 (the successor_count slot,
maintained by add_cfg_edge). Returns 0 for null block.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Read once before every forward CFG walk. Inlines to a single load.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "get_block_successor_count" that takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 56
End Process

@Reasoning
Wires a control-flow edge between two blocks, updating the predecessor /
successor lists on both sides AND the CFG's master edge list. The
bidirectional encoding is fundamental: every forward dataflow pass walks
successor lists and every reverse dataflow pass walks predecessor lists,
so both sides MUST agree. The separate cfg-level edge list at offset 32
exists so dominance computation can iterate edges without re-walking the
block graph.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Linear-scans the cfg's blocks list at offset 16 (length at offset 24) to
locate the MIRBasicBlock records matching pred_id and succ_id. If either is
missing, returns 0 — the caller must have registered both blocks via
add_block_to_cfg first. Otherwise: appends succ_id to pred's successors
list (offset 48) and increments pred.successor_count (offset 56); appends
pred_id to succ's predecessors list (offset 32) and increments
succ.predecessor_count (offset 40); appends (pred_id, succ_id) as two
entries to cfg.edges (offset 32) and increments cfg.edge_count (offset 40).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Three List appends and three counter increments. The block-id lookup
guarantees that successor / predecessor pointers are valid before any
mutation. Null cfg short-circuits.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "add_cfg_edge" that takes cfg as Integer, pred_id as Integer, succ_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

    Let pred_block be 0
    Let succ_block be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, i
        Let block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 0

        If block_id is equal to pred_id:
            Set pred_block to block
        End If

        If block_id is equal to succ_id:
            Set succ_block to block
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If pred_block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If succ_block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pred_successors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with pred_block, 48
    proc append from List with pred_successors, succ_id
    Let pred_succ_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with pred_block, 56
    Set pred_succ_count to pred_succ_count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with pred_block, 56, pred_succ_count

    Let succ_predecessors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with succ_block, 32
    proc append from List with succ_predecessors, pred_id
    Let succ_pred_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with succ_block, 40
    Set succ_pred_count to succ_pred_count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with succ_block, 40, succ_pred_count

    Let edges be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 32
    proc append from List with edges, pred_id
    proc append from List with edges, succ_id
    Let edge_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 40
    Set edge_count to edge_count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 40, edge_count

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Registers a basic block in the CFG's master block list. This is the inverse
companion to add_cfg_edge: blocks must be physically present in the CFG before
their CFG edges can be wired up, otherwise add_cfg_edge's block-id lookup
loop will fail to locate them.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Appends the block pointer to the blocks list at offset 16 of the CFG record
and increments the block_count field at offset 24. The block's own internal
edge lists are NOT touched here — add_cfg_edge is responsible for predecessor
and successor wiring. Returns 1 on success or 0 if either pointer is null.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_block_to_cfg" that takes cfg as Integer, block as Integer returns Integer:
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
    proc append from List with blocks, block

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24
    Set count to count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24, count

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the CFG's entry block — the block reached on function entry. The
entry block is the root of every forward CFG analysis (dominance, available
expressions, reachability) and is the only block in the function with no
predecessors. The verifier checks that the entry block has predecessor
count zero.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRCFG offset 0 (the entry_block slot, set by
set_cfg_entry_block during CFG construction). Returns 0 for null cfg.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_cfg_entry_block" that takes cfg as Integer returns Integer:
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Sets the CFG's entry block. Called during HIR-to-MIR lowering once the
first block of the function has been created; later passes (block
splitting, loop rotation) may also need to update the entry pointer if
they introduce a new pre-header that dominates the original entry.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes block pointer at MIRCFG offset 0. Returns 1 on success, 0 for null
cfg. Caller is responsible for ensuring the new entry block has been added
to the CFG via add_block_to_cfg first.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_cfg_entry_block" that takes cfg as Integer, block as Integer returns Integer:
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 0, block
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the CFG's exit block — the unique synthetic block that postdominates
every return / unwind. Reverse dataflow analyses (liveness) start here, and
function-epilogue lowering emits its prologue against this block. A unique
exit simplifies postdominance: without it, multiple returns would produce
multiple roots in the reverse CFG.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRCFG offset 8 (the exit_block slot). Returns 0 for
null cfg, or for a CFG that has not yet had set_cfg_exit_block called
(during very early construction).
@End Implementation

Process called "get_cfg_exit_block" that takes cfg as Integer returns Integer:
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Sets the CFG's exit block. Called during HIR-to-MIR lowering once the
synthetic exit / return-merge block has been allocated. Code-motion passes
that introduce additional return paths must redirect them to merge into
this block rather than allocating new exit blocks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes block pointer at MIRCFG offset 8. Returns 1 on success, 0 for null
cfg. Caller must have added the block via add_block_to_cfg first.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_cfg_exit_block" that takes cfg as Integer, block as Integer returns Integer:
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 8, block
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Allocates a fresh SSA value-id, monotonically increasing per function. The
SSA invariant requires that every value-id within a function be unique so
that def-use tracking, dominator analysis, and the value-to-instruction map
can use the id as a stable key. Per-function (not per-program) numbering
keeps ids dense and allows them to fit easily in 32 bits even for very
large functions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the next_value_id counter at MIRFunction offset 56, returns it as the
allocated id, then writes back next_id + 1. Returns 0 for a null function
pointer; legitimate value-ids begin at whatever the SSA construction context
seeded the counter with (typically 1000+ to distinguish from constants).
@End Implementation

Process called "allocate_value_id" that takes function as Integer returns Integer:
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let next_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function, 56
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 56, next_id plus 1

    Return next_id
End Process

@Reasoning
Allocates a fresh basic-block id within a CFG, monotonically increasing.
Block ids are used as keys by add_cfg_edge (to locate predecessor and
successor blocks in the master block list) and by dominator analysis to
index its dominator tree arrays, so dense, unique numbering is required.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the next_block_id counter at CFG offset 48, returns it as the
allocated id, then writes back next_id + 1. Returns 0 for a null cfg
pointer. The counter is initialised by create_mir_cfg.
@End Implementation

Process called "allocate_block_id" that takes cfg as Integer returns Integer:
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let next_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 48
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cfg, 48, next_id plus 1

    Return next_id
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Metadata Accessor Functions
Note: Metadata provides extensibility for optimization hints, debug info, profiling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the metadata pointer attached to an instruction. Metadata carries
out-of-band information that does not affect semantics but is critical for
diagnostics and optimisation hints: source variable names, source location,
profile counts, alias-set tags, inlining hints. Each pass that consumes
metadata must tolerate a null pointer (no metadata attached).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRNode offset 64 (the metadata slot per the Type
definition). Returns 0 for null node.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_mir_node_metadata" that takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 64
End Process

@Reasoning
Attaches a metadata pointer to an instruction. Called by HIR-to-MIR
lowering to carry forward source-level information (variable names, source
locations) and by analysis passes that compute and cache results
(profile-derived branch weights, alias sets).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes metadata pointer at MIRNode offset 64. Returns 1 on success, 0 for
null node. The metadata pointer is borrowed; the metadata's lifetime must
exceed the MIRNode's.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_mir_node_metadata" that takes node as Integer, metadata as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, metadata
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the metadata pointer attached to a MIRFunction. Function-level
metadata carries inlining hints (always_inline, never_inline), calling-
convention overrides, profile-based hot/cold classification, and link-time
attributes (weak, hidden, no_unwind). The LIR builder and the linker
front-end read this on every function it lowers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRFunction offset 88 (the authoritative metadata slot
per P2-D offset audit 2026-05-24). Returns 0 for null function.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_mir_function_metadata" that takes function as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: metadata field is at offset 88 per Type definition (P2-D offset audit 2026-05-24)
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function, 88
End Process

@Reasoning
Sets the metadata pointer on a MIRFunction. Called by HIR-to-MIR lowering
to forward source-declared attributes (inline-hints, linkage), and by
profile-guided optimisation to attach hotness data after profile-load.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes metadata pointer at MIRFunction offset 88 (authoritative offset per
P2-D offset audit). Returns 1 on success, 0 for null function.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_mir_function_metadata" that takes function as Integer, metadata as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: metadata field is at offset 88 per Type definition (P2-D offset audit 2026-05-24)
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 88, metadata
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the HIR-side definition node from which this MIRFunction was
lowered. Diagnostics use this to trace MIR-level errors back to source
location; reverse-translation tools (RunaConvert) read this to recover
the source-level structure of the function for round-tripping.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRFunction offset 72 (the authoritative hir_node slot
per P2-D offset audit 2026-05-24). Returns 0 for null function or for
functions synthesised by the compiler with no HIR origin.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_mir_function_hir_node" that takes function as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: hir_node field is at offset 72 per Type definition (P2-D offset audit 2026-05-24)
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function, 72
End Process

@Reasoning
Sets the HIR back-reference on a MIRFunction. Called by HIR-to-MIR
lowering at function-creation time; rarely re-set later, except by
specialisation / cloning passes that need to preserve a synthetic
function's link to the original HIR.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes hir_node pointer at MIRFunction offset 72. Returns 1 on success, 0
for null function.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_mir_function_hir_node" that takes function as Integer, hir_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: hir_node field is at offset 72 per Type definition (P2-D offset audit 2026-05-24)
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with function, 72, hir_node
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Predicate test for "is this function externally defined (FFI binding)?".
The is_external flag determines whether the LIR builder emits a function
body or just an extern declaration; inlining, devirtualisation, and tail-
call all skip external functions because their bodies are not visible.
Every pass that walks the function list reads through this accessor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRFunction offset 80 (the authoritative is_external
slot; all consumers — inlining, devirt, tail_call, lto, lir_builder —
read at offset 80). Returns 0 for null function (treated as
"not external", the safe default for a partial record).
@End Implementation

Process called "is_external_function" that takes function as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Reads is_external at the authoritative offset 80.
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function, 80
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the program-level metadata pointer. Program metadata carries
build configuration (target triple, optimisation level), link-graph
attributes (which functions are exported), and global profile data
(per-module branch weight totals).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRProgram offset 56 (the metadata slot per the Type
definition). Returns 0 for null program.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_mir_program_metadata" that takes program as Integer returns Integer:
    If program is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with program, 56
End Process

@Reasoning
Sets program-level metadata. Called once by the compiler driver after
target / options resolution, and again after PGO profile-load to attach
per-program branch weights.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes metadata pointer at MIRProgram offset 56. Returns 1 on success, 0
for null program.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_mir_program_metadata" that takes program as Integer, metadata as Integer returns Integer:
    If program is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with program, 56, metadata
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MIR Analysis Helper Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Predicate testing whether an opcode terminates a basic block. The block
verifier requires every block to end with exactly one terminator and to
contain no terminator in any non-final position. CFG construction uses
this test to decide where to close one block and open the next when
emitting MIR linearly. Lowering uses it to identify points where the
machine-code emitter must emit branch instructions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if opcode is one of MIR_BRANCH, MIR_JUMP, MIR_RETURN, MIR_SWITCH;
otherwise returns 0. Sequential opcode-equals comparisons are used rather
than a range check because terminator opcodes are non-contiguous in the
20000+ MIR opcode space.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Inlining candidate; called on every instruction during block-bounded
optimisation passes. Compiles to four compare-and-branch sequences.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "is_terminator" that takes opcode as Integer returns Integer:
    If opcode is equal to MIR_BRANCH:
        Return 1
    End If

    If opcode is equal to MIR_JUMP:
        Return 1
    End If

    If opcode is equal to MIR_RETURN:
        Return 1
    End If

    If opcode is equal to MIR_SWITCH:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Predicate testing whether an opcode is a phi-node — the SSA merge
instruction. Phi nodes are special-cased throughout the compiler: they MUST
appear at the start of a block (before all non-phi instructions), they are
not "regular" computations during instruction scheduling, and they are
eliminated by SSA destruction during register allocation rather than
lowered directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if opcode equals MIR_PHI, 0 otherwise. Single comparison since
there is exactly one phi opcode.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Hot inline candidate; tested by every pass that walks block instructions.
Compiles to a single compare-and-branch.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "is_phi_node" that takes opcode as Integer returns Integer:
    If opcode is equal to MIR_PHI:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Predicate matching every binary arithmetic/bitwise/comparison opcode in one
test. The MIR opcode numbering deliberately groups arithmetic ops (20002 to
20016 = MIR_ADD to MIR_SAR) and comparison ops (20100 to 20105 = MIR_EQ to
MIR_GE) into contiguous ranges so a two-range test is sufficient — no
per-opcode comparison chain is required.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Two range checks: [MIR_ADD..MIR_SAR] covers the arithmetic and bitwise
operations, [MIR_EQ..MIR_GE] covers the relational comparisons. The numeric
gap between MIR_SAR (20016) and MIR_EQ (20100) is intentional — unary
operations and reserved opcode space sit between them and must NOT be
classified as binary.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Inlining candidate: the function compiles to two pairs of compare-and-branch.
Used in hot loops during instruction selection and peephole optimization.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "is_binary_op" that takes opcode as Integer returns Integer:
    If opcode is greater than or equal to MIR_ADD:
        If opcode is less than or equal to MIR_SAR:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If opcode is greater than or equal to MIR_EQ:
        If opcode is less than or equal to MIR_GE:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Predicate testing whether an opcode is a memory-access operation (load,
store, address-of, dereference, field-access). Alias analysis must conservatively
treat memory ops as potentially aliasing; mem2reg promotes only loads /
stores of address-not-taken values to SSA registers; load / store
elimination matches sequences of memory ops. All three passes need a fast
O(1) classification.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Range check: returns 1 if opcode is in [MIR_LOAD..MIR_DEREF] (the contiguous
20200..20206 block in the MIR opcode numbering scheme), 0 otherwise. The
range layout makes this a two-comparison test independent of how many
memory opcodes exist.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Hot inline candidate; tested in inner loops of alias analysis and
load/store elimination. Compiles to a pair of compare-and-branch.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "is_memory_op" that takes opcode as Integer returns Integer:
    If opcode is greater than or equal to MIR_LOAD:
        If opcode is less than or equal to MIR_DEREF:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Predicate distinguishing value-producing instructions (most arithmetic, loads,
calls) from side-effect-only instructions (stores, branches, returns, nops).
Used by DCE: if an instruction does not produce a value and has no other
side effect, it can be deleted; if it produces a value with no uses, it can
be deleted; if neither, it must be kept.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Enumerated denial list: every non-producing opcode (NOP, STORE, STORE_FIELD,
BRANCH, JUMP, RETURN) returns 0. All other opcodes default to 1 (producing).
Default-to-producing is the correct bias because the producing set is much
larger than the non-producing set.
@End Implementation

Process called "produces_value" that takes opcode as Integer returns Integer:
    If opcode is equal to MIR_NOP:
        Return 0
    End If

    If opcode is equal to MIR_STORE:
        Return 0
    End If

    If opcode is equal to MIR_STORE_FIELD:
        Return 0
    End If

    If opcode is equal to MIR_BRANCH:
        Return 0
    End If

    If opcode is equal to MIR_JUMP:
        Return 0
    End If

    If opcode is equal to MIR_RETURN:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MIR Debug Printing Functions
Note: Essential for optimizer development and debugging
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Translates a MIR opcode integer into its textual mnemonic. The debug
printer, the verifier's error messages, and the dump-MIR tools all rely on
human-readable opcode names. The opcode integer space (20000+) is sparse
and not amenable to a table lookup without a dense-mapping table, so this
function uses a sequential equality-chain that is simple to extend when
new opcodes are added.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Compares opcode against every known MIR_* constant in order and returns a
freshly-allocated string duplicate of the matching mnemonic. Returns the
duplicate of "unknown" for any opcode that does not match a known
constant. Every return path duplicates the string so the caller owns the
result and must deallocate it after use, avoiding shared-buffer aliasing.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Each successful return path allocates a fresh string via
StringCore.string_duplicate. Caller MUST deallocate; failure to do so leaks
a small heap block per call. No bounds-unsafe operations occur.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "opcode_to_string" that takes opcode as Integer returns Integer:
    If opcode is equal to MIR_NOP:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "nop"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to MIR_CONST:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "const"
