@Reasoning
Formats a single MIRNode as a one-line textual representation in the
canonical "%dst = op %src1, %src2, %src3" form. This is the lowest level
of MIR pretty-printing, called by mir_basic_block_to_string for every
instruction in a block. The format mirrors LLVM-style SSA dumps so that
developers used to other SSA IRs can read MIR dumps without translation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads opcode (offset 0), value_id (8), and operands 1/2/3 (offsets 16/24/32)
from the MIRNode. Builds the result string incrementally: emits "%N = "
when value_id is non-zero, appends the opcode mnemonic from
opcode_to_string, then appends " %op1", ", %op2", ", %op3" for each
non-zero operand. Every temporary string (value_str, op1_str, op2_str,
op3_str, opcode_str) is deallocated after concatenation. Returns "<null>"
for a null node pointer.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Allocates one result string and several temporary strings; every temporary
is explicitly deallocated via Layout.deallocate after concatenation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "mir_node_to_string" that takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null>"
    End If

    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
    Let value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
    Let op1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
    Let op2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24
    Let op3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32

    Let opcode_str be proc opcode_to_string with opcode

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with ""

    If value_id is not equal to 0:
        Let value_str be proc integer_to_string from StringCore with value_id
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, "%"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, value_str
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, " = "
        proc deallocate from Layout with value_str
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, opcode_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with opcode_str

    If op1 is not equal to 0:
        Let op1_str be proc integer_to_string from StringCore with op1
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, " %"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, op1_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with op1_str
    End If

    If op2 is not equal to 0:
        Let op2_str be proc integer_to_string from StringCore with op2
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, ", %"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, op2_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with op2_str
    End If

    If op3 is not equal to 0:
        Let op3_str be proc integer_to_string from StringCore with op3
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, ", %"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, op3_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with op3_str
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Formats an entire basic block — label followed by every instruction
indented under it — as a multi-line textual block. Used by
mir_cfg_to_string to print every block in the CFG. The conventional
"label:\n  inst1\n  inst2\n" layout matches IR-dump conventions in other
SSA compilers, making MIR dumps visually familiar.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads block_id (offset 0), label (offset 8), instructions list (offset 16),
and instruction count (offset 24). Emits the label when present, otherwise
synthesises "block_<block_id>". Appends ":\n", then iterates the
instruction list, calling mir_node_to_string for each instruction,
prefixing two-space indent and a newline. Every per-instruction string is
deallocated after concatenation. Returns "<null block>" for null block.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Allocates one result string and a temporary per instruction; each
temporary is explicitly deallocated after concatenation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "mir_basic_block_to_string" that takes block as Integer returns Integer:
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null block>"
    End If

    Let block_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 0
    Let label be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 8
    Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
    Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with ""

    If label is not equal to 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, label
    Otherwise:
        Let block_id_str be proc integer_to_string from StringCore with block_id
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, "block_"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, block_id_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with block_id_str
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, ":\n"

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than inst_count:
        Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i
        Let inst_str be proc mir_node_to_string with inst
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, "  "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, inst_str
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, "\n"
        proc deallocate from Layout with inst_str
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Formats the entire CFG by emitting every block in list order. Used by
mir_function_to_string after the function-signature header. Block-list
order is insertion order — not topological order — because dumping in
insertion order preserves the developer's mental model of how the CFG
was constructed; topological dumping is a separate dump-mode that the
optimiser-debug subsystem provides.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the blocks list (offset 16) and block count (offset 24) from the
CFG. Prepends "CFG:\n", iterates blocks and concatenates
mir_basic_block_to_string output for each, separated by newlines. Every
per-block string is deallocated after concatenation. Returns "<null cfg>"
for null CFG.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Allocates one result and a temporary per block; each temporary is
explicitly deallocated.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "mir_cfg_to_string" that takes cfg as Integer returns Integer:
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null cfg>"
    End If

    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "CFG:\n"

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, i
        Let block_str be proc mir_basic_block_to_string with block
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, block_str
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, "\n"
        proc deallocate from Layout with block_str
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Formats a complete MIR function — its signature header followed by its
CFG. The function-level dump is the unit the developer typically wants:
a single function's full SSA representation across all blocks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads name (offset 0) and cfg (offset 8) from the MIRFunction. Emits
"function <name>:\n" (using "<anonymous>" if name is null), then appends
mir_cfg_to_string(cfg) if cfg is non-null. The cfg-string temporary is
deallocated after concatenation. Returns "<null function>" for null
function.
@End Implementation

Process called "mir_function_to_string" that takes function as Integer returns Integer:
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "<null function>"
    End If

    Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function, 0
    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with function, 8

    Let result be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "function "

    If name is not equal to 0:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, name
    Otherwise:
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, "<anonymous>"
    End If

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, ":\n"

    If cfg is not equal to 0:
        Let cfg_str be proc mir_cfg_to_string with cfg
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringCore with result, cfg_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with cfg_str
    End If

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Top-level MIR dump entry point. Walks every function in the program and
prints its formatted representation to the Display sink. Used by
--dump-mir and by the optimiser-debug subsystem after every optimisation
pass that has tracing enabled.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the functions list (offset 0) and function count (offset 8) from
MIRProgram. Iterates the list, calling mir_function_to_string for each
function, Display-ing the result, then deallocating the per-function
string. Returns 1 on success, 0 if program is null.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Per-function string allocations are explicitly deallocated after Display;
no temporaries are leaked across iterations.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "print_mir_program" that takes program as Integer returns Integer:
    If program is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with program, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with program, 8

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let function be proc get from List with functions, i
        Let func_str be proc mir_function_to_string with function
        Display func_str
        proc deallocate from Layout with func_str
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: SSA CONSTRUCTION HELPER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
Predicate test for "does this instruction define an SSA value?". SSA
construction (Cytron-style phi placement) walks every instruction in
every block and partitions them into definitions and non-definitions;
this predicate is the partitioning function. A non-zero value_id is the
canonical encoding of "this instruction produces a value".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads value_id from MIRNode offset 8 and returns 1 if non-zero, 0
otherwise. Returns 0 for null inst_ptr.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Inner-loop predicate during SSA construction; inlines to a single load
and compare.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "instruction_defines_variable" that takes inst_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Null check
    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get value_id from MIRNode (offset 8)
    Let value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 8

    Note: If value_id is non-zero, this instruction defines a variable
    If value_id is not equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Recovers the source-level variable name that this instruction defines,
falling back to a synthetic SSA name when no source name is available.
Diagnostics, debug-info emission, and the optimiser-debug subsystem all
need a human-readable name for every SSA value. The "temp_N" fallback
mirrors LLVM's %0, %1, %2 convention for unnamed values.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
First calls instruction_defines_variable to short-circuit on non-producing
instructions. Reads value_id (offset 8) and metadata_ptr (offset 64).
If metadata_ptr is non-null, reads the variable_name pointer from
MIRMetadata offset 0; returns it when non-null. Otherwise allocates a
64-byte buffer and writes "temp_" followed by the base-10 ASCII
representation of value_id (digit count computed by repeated division;
digits stored in reverse and placed via offset arithmetic). Null
terminator at the final position. Returns 0 for null inst_ptr.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Synthetic-name path allocates a 64-byte heap buffer. The base-10
expansion loop is bounded by digit_count which is itself bounded by 20
(int64 maximum), well under the 64-byte buffer. Buffer is null-terminated
after digit emission. Caller owns the returned buffer and must
deallocate it.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_instruction_defined_variable" that takes inst_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Null check
    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if instruction defines a variable
    Let defines_var be proc instruction_defines_variable with inst_ptr
    If defines_var is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get value_id (offset 8)
    Let value_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 8

    Note: Get metadata from MIRNode (offset 64)
    Let metadata_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 64

    If metadata_ptr is not equal to 0:
        Note: Get variable name from MIRMetadata (offset 0)
        Let variable_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with metadata_ptr, 0

        If variable_name is not equal to 0:
            Note: Found variable name in metadata - return it
            Return variable_name
        End If
    End If

    Note: No metadata or no variable name - generate SSA name
    Note: SSA temporaries like "temp_N" are appropriate for IR (similar to LLVM %0, %1)
    Let name_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 64

    Note: Create string "temp_"
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 0, 116  Note: 't'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 1, 101  Note: 'e'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 2, 109  Note: 'm'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 3, 112  Note: 'p'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 4, 95   Note: '_'

    Note: Convert value_id to string and append
    Let pos be 5
    Let temp_value be value_id
    Let digit_count be 0

    Note: Count digits
    Let temp_copy be temp_value
    While temp_copy is greater than 0:
        Set temp_copy to temp_copy divided by 10
        Set digit_count to digit_count plus 1
    End While

    Note: Handle zero case
    If digit_count is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, pos, 48  Note: '0'
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Note: Extract digits in reverse order
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than digit_count:
            Let digit be temp_value modulo by 10
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, pos plus digit_count minus i minus 1, digit plus 48
            Set temp_value to temp_value divided by 10
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Set pos to pos plus digit_count
    End If

    Note: Null terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, pos, 0

    Return name_buffer
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the HIRTypeInfo pointer for an instruction's result type. Semantic
duplicate of get_mir_node_type retained here under the SSA-construction
naming because the SSA-construction code paths consistently use the
"instruction" vocabulary; aliasing for readability of the call sites.
Used by type-driven phi-node typing and by SSA destruction's register-
class assignment.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the int64 at MIRNode offset 40 (the type_info slot). Returns 0 for
null inst_ptr. Functionally equivalent to get_mir_node_type — the two
accessors share an offset to allow either vocabulary to be used at any
call site.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_instruction_result_type" that takes inst_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Null check
    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get type_info from MIRNode (offset 40)
    Let type_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 40
    Return type_info
End Process

@Reasoning
Inserts an instruction at the beginning of a basic block. This operation
is dedicated to phi-node placement: the SSA invariant requires phi nodes
to appear strictly before all non-phi instructions in their block, so the
appender path (add_instruction_to_block) is the wrong primitive for them.
SSA-construction's phi-insertion phase calls this once per phi.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the block's instructions List at offset 16 and length at offset 24
(canonical MIRBasicBlock layout from create_mir_basic_block). If the list
is null, allocates a fresh one and stores it back. Allocates a NEW List,
appends inst_ptr first, then appends every existing instruction in order —
yielding a list with the new instruction at index 0. Destroys the old list,
writes the new list pointer back to the block at offset 16, increments the
instruction_count at offset 24, and writes the instruction's parent_block
back-pointer at MIRNode offset 56. Returns 1 on success, 0 if either
pointer is null. All offsets match the create_mir_basic_block writer
and the get_block_instructions / get_block_instruction_count readers in
this same file.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Allocates a new List, destroys the old one. The destroy is safe because
the new list now holds all the original instructions plus the new one;
the old list's storage is freed but its contents (the instruction
pointers) live on under the new list.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "insert_instruction_at_block_start" that takes block_ptr as Integer, inst_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Null checks
    If block_ptr is equal to 0 or inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get instructions list (offset 16 - canonical MIRBasicBlock layout)
    Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block_ptr, 16
    If instructions is equal to 0:
        Note: Create new instructions list
        Set instructions to proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block_ptr, 16, instructions
    End If

    Note: Insert at beginning of list
    Note: Create new list with inst_ptr first
    Let new_instructions be proc create from List
    proc append from List with new_instructions, inst_ptr

    Note: Append existing instructions (count at offset 24)
    Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block_ptr, 24
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than inst_count:
        Let existing_inst be proc get from List with instructions, i
        proc append from List with new_instructions, existing_inst
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Replace instructions list
    proc destroy from List with instructions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block_ptr, 16, new_instructions

    Note: Update instruction count (offset 24)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with block_ptr, 24, inst_count plus 1

    Note: Set instruction's parent block (offset 56 in MIRNode)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 56, block_ptr

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns a freshly-allocated List containing only the non-zero operand
value-ids of an instruction. Compared to direct access via
get_mir_node_operand(node, idx), this packaged form is convenient for
passes that need to enumerate "every operand used by this instruction"
without dispatching on operand-arity by opcode — e.g. liveness analysis
when it tags every operand as a "use" at the instruction's program point.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a fresh List (TIER 3 owned heap). Reads operand1 (offset 16),
operand2 (offset 24), operand3 (offset 32); appends each non-zero value
to the list. Returns the (possibly empty) list. For null inst_ptr,
returns an empty list rather than 0 so the caller can iterate
uniformly.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
List allocation is the only heap mutation. Caller owns the returned list
and must destroy it when done.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_instruction_operands" that takes inst_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create result list
    Let operands be proc create from List

    Note: Null check
    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return operands
    End If

    Note: Get operand1 (offset 16)
    Let op1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 16
    If op1 is not equal to 0:
        proc append from List with operands, op1
    End If

    Note: Get operand2 (offset 24)
    Let op2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 24
    If op2 is not equal to 0:
        proc append from List with operands, op2
    End If

    Note: Get operand3 (offset 32)
    Let op3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 32
    If op3 is not equal to 0:
        proc append from List with operands, op3
    End If

    Return operands
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the count of non-zero operand slots without allocating an
operand list. Cheaper than get_instruction_operands when the caller only
needs the count (e.g. branching by arity in the verifier, or budgeting
register pressure during scheduling).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads operand1 (offset 16), operand2 (offset 24), operand3 (offset 32);
increments a counter for each non-zero value. Returns 0..3. Returns 0
for null inst_ptr.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Allocation-free; inlines to three loads, three compares, three increments.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "get_instruction_operand_count" that takes inst_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Null check
    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be 0

    Note: Check operand1 (offset 16)
    Let op1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 16
    If op1 is not equal to 0:
        Set count to count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Check operand2 (offset 24)
    Let op2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 24
    If op2 is not equal to 0:
        Set count to count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Check operand3 (offset 32)
    Let op3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 32
    If op3 is not equal to 0:
        Set count to count plus 1
    End If

    Return count
End Process

@Reasoning
Predicate testing whether an operand value-id refers to an SSA variable
or to a constant. The convention "id >= 1000 ⇒ variable" is established
by ssa.runa's context initialiser, which seeds next_value_id at 1000 so
all subsequently allocated SSA ids are guaranteed to be in the variable
range. Constants encode their value directly in the low-numbered id space.
This classification is needed by every pass that lowers MIR to a target
ISA where constants and registers take different operand encodings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Single comparison: returns 1 if operand_value_id >= 1000, else 0.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Inlining candidate; compiles to a single compare-and-set-flag sequence.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "operand_is_variable" that takes operand_value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SSA value IDs start from 1000 (as set in ssa.runa context creation)
    If operand_value_id is greater than or equal to 1000:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Recovers a human-readable variable name for an operand value-id, by
first locating its defining instruction in the function's
value_to_instruction map and then reading the metadata-attached source
name. Falls back to a synthetic "v_<id>" name when no defining
instruction exists (constants, function arguments before SSA registration)
or when the instruction has no metadata. Diagnostics, debug-info, and
the optimiser-debug subsystem all consume this.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
On null function_ptr, takes the synthetic-name path immediately. Otherwise,
calls lookup_defining_instruction; on hit, reads metadata_ptr at MIRNode
offset 64; on metadata hit, reads variable_name at MIRMetadata offset 0
and returns it when non-null. Synthetic-name path: allocates a 64-byte
buffer, writes "v_" (ASCII 118, 95) at offsets 0/1, then computes the
base-10 ASCII representation of operand_value_id using a digit-count loop
followed by a reverse-order digit-emission loop, and null-terminates.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope
Synthetic-name path allocates a 64-byte buffer. The base-10 expansion is
bounded by 20 digits (int64 maximum), well under buffer size. Caller owns
the returned buffer when it falls through to the synthetic path; when the
metadata path returns a borrowed string, that string is owned by the
MIRMetadata record.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_operand_variable_name" that takes function_ptr as Integer, operand_value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If function_ptr is equal to 0:
        Note: No function context - generate SSA name
        Let name_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 64
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 0, 118  Note: 'v'
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 1, 95   Note: '_'
        Let value_str be proc integer_to_string from StringCore with operand_value_id
        Note: Append value_id string after "v_"
        Return name_buffer
    End If

    Note: Look up defining instruction for this value
    Let inst_ptr be proc lookup_defining_instruction with function_ptr, operand_value_id

    If inst_ptr is not equal to 0:
        Note: Found defining instruction - try to get metadata
        Let metadata_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 64

        If metadata_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Note: Get variable name from MIRMetadata (offset 0)
            Let variable_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with metadata_ptr, 0

            If variable_name is not equal to 0:
                Note: Found variable name in metadata - return it
                Return variable_name
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: No metadata or no defining instruction - generate SSA value name
    Set name_buffer to proc allocate from Layout with 64

    Note: Create string "v_"
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 0, 118  Note: 'v'
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, 1, 95   Note: '_'

    Note: Convert value_id to string
    Let pos be 2
    Let temp_value be operand_value_id
    Let digit_count be 0

    Note: Count digits
    Let temp_copy be temp_value
    While temp_copy is greater than 0:
        Set temp_copy to temp_copy divided by 10
        Set digit_count to digit_count plus 1
    End While

    Note: Handle zero case
    If digit_count is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, pos, 48  Note: '0'
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Note: Extract digits
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than digit_count:
            Let digit be temp_value modulo by 10
            proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, pos plus digit_count minus i minus 1, digit plus 48
            Set temp_value to temp_value divided by 10
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Set pos to pos plus digit_count
    End If

    Note: Null terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with name_buffer, pos, 0

    Return name_buffer
End Process

@Reasoning
Updates one operand slot of an instruction to a new SSA value-id. Used
during SSA renaming (Cytron's rename pass) to retarget operands to the
correct reaching definition. The renaming pass walks the dominator tree
and at every use point rewrites the operand to refer to the SSA name on
top of the current variable's renaming stack — this is the per-operand
write that pass invokes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Zero-based index dispatch (matching the convention used by SSA-rename's
operand iteration) and writes new_value_id at MIRNode offset 16 (index 0
⇒ operand1), 24 (index 1 ⇒ operand2), or 32 (index 2 ⇒ operand3). Returns
1 on successful write, 0 for null inst_ptr or out-of-range index. Caller
is responsible for maintaining def-use chains (remove old use, add new
use) — this primitive only rewrites the slot.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_operand_ssa_value_id" that takes inst_ptr as Integer, operand_index as Integer, new_value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Null check
    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set operand based on index
    If operand_index is equal to 0:
        Note: Set operand1 (offset 16)
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 16, new_value_id
        Return 1
    End If

    If operand_index is equal to 1:
        Note: Set operand2 (offset 24)
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 24, new_value_id
        Return 1
    End If

    If operand_index is equal to 2:
        Note: Set operand3 (offset 32)
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 32, new_value_id
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Invalid operand index
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Sets the result SSA value-id of an instruction. The renaming companion to
set_operand_ssa_value_id: SSA rename walks every definition site and
allocates a fresh SSA name for it, then writes that name as the
instruction's result via this function. Functionally equivalent to
set_mir_node_value_id; retained under the SSA-construction vocabulary
for call-site readability.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Writes new_value_id at MIRNode offset 8 (the value_id slot). Returns 1
on success, 0 for null inst_ptr. Like set_mir_node_value_id, does not
register the new id in the function's value_to_instruction map — caller
must call register_value_definition separately to keep that map in sync.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_instruction_result_value_id" that takes inst_ptr as Integer, new_value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Null check
    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set value_id (offset 8 in MIRNode)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 8, new_value_id
    Return 1
End Process
